⚡ Launching an NGINX Web Server on an Amazon EC2 ☁️
I will be showcasing the steps I used to launch an NGINX web server on an Amazon EC2 instance and map it to a domain purchased through Cloudflare.

🔹 Step 1: We will need to purchase a domain. In this case, I had used Cloudflare.

🔹 Step 2: Launch an EC2 Instance
Go onto AWS, log in and launch a EC2 instance with the following information:
AMI: Amazon Linux 2023
Instance Type: t3.micro
Create a Keyfile and save it appropriately, this will matter for the next step.
Security Group Inbound Rules:
Port 22 (SSH) – Your IP
Port 80 (HTTP) – 0.0.0.0/0
Port 443 (HTTPS) – 0.0.0.0/0

🔹 Step 3: Note the Public IPv4 Address
After launching, copy the Public IPv4 address that appears.
This will be used later to point your domain to the server.

🔹 Step 4: Connect to the EC2 Instance via SSH
Run this command in your terminal💻 :
This will help find the correct location of where you have saved the keyfile. Also you will need the IP address you had copied.
ssh -i /path/to/key.pem ec2-user@<EC2_PUBLIC_IP>
If you face a key permissions error: run chmod 400 ~/Downloads/yourkeyname.pem

🔹 Step 5: At this point, we will need to install NGINX
Run these commands in your terminal💻:

sudo yum update -y
sudo yum install -y nginx
sudo systemctl start nginx
sudo systemctl enable nginx

🔹 Step 6: Login to your Cloudfare account, and create an A record for your domain. Enter in your Public IPV4 address you noted down earlier.

🔹 Step 7: Go back onto the terminal, and confirm domain information by running: nslookup <Your domain>

🔹 Step 8: Page customisation
To customise your page, run the following
sudo yum install nginx -y sudo systemctl start nginx

🔹 Step 9: Finally search your domain name/ip address on the browser and your domain should appear!

There you have it, an NGINX web server run on an Amazon EC2, directed to your custom domain!
